    • addToMap

      public static <K> void addToMap​(java.util.Map<K,​java.lang.Number> m, K k, java.lang.Number i)
      Adds to a mapped number. If m does not already contain the key k then i is mapped to k. Otherwise the value for k is obtained from m and i is added to it using Generic_Math.add(java.lang.Number, java.lang.Number). This may result in infinite values being added to m or ArithmeticExceptions being thrown all depending on the result of any additions as calculated via Generic_Math.add(java.lang.Number, java.lang.Number).
      Type Parameters:
      K - Key
      Parameters:
      m - The map that is to be added to.
      k - The key which value is added to or initialised.
      i - The amount to be added to the map.

      Adds v to the ArrayList in m indexed by k if the last element of m is not already the value v. If m does not already contain k then a new ArrayList of type V is created with v added to it and this is added to the map using the key k.

    • addToMapInteger

      public static <K> java.lang.Integer addToMapInteger​(java.util.Map<K,​java.lang.Integer> m, K k, java.lang.Integer v)
      Adds v to the value of m corresponding with k.If there is no such k in m or the value m.get(k) is null then v is added to m addressed by k. This does not check if the resulting value overflows. If this might happen then perhaps use either:
      • addToMap(java.util.Map, java.lang.Object, java.lang.Object) instead which would in such a case throw an ArithmeticException.that case.
      • addToMapBigInteger(java.util.Map, java.lang.Object, java.math.BigInteger) instead as BigIntegers do not overflow.
      Type Parameters:
      K - Key
      Parameters:
      m - TreeMap
      k - key
      v - value
      Returns:
      The resulting value in m mapped by k.

    • addToMap

      public static <K,​ V1 extends java.lang.Number,​ V2 extends java.lang.Number> void addToMap​(java.util.Map<K,​V1> u, java.util.Map<K,​V2> uf)
      This will add the values in uf to the values in u for any existing keys. Where keys in u do not exist, the the numerical value of these in uf are put in u. This may result in infinite numbers being values in u (where the resulting addition is beyond the bounds of the type of V1). Existing keys in u that are mapped to null values are removed. NaN values may also be added to u if infinite values added are the opposite infinities. ArithmeticExceptions might also be throws if NaN type values are attempted to be added to types that cannot represent NaN.
      Type Parameters:
      K - The types of key in u and f.
      V1 - The type of Number values in u.
      V2 - The type of Number values in uf.
      Parameters:
      u - The map to updated by adding to the values from uf.
      uf - The map to update u from by adding values.

    • addToMapLong

      public static <K> long addToMapLong​(java.util.Map<K,​java.lang.Long> m, K k, java.lang.Long v)
      Adds v to the value of m corresponding with k.If there is no such k in m or the value m.get(k) is null then v is added to m addressed by k. This does not check if the resulting value overflows. If this might happen then either check or instead use either:
      • addToMap(java.util.Map, java.lang.Object, java.lang.Object) - which would in such a case throw an ArithmeticException in the case of a numerical overflow.
      • addToMapBigInteger(java.util.Map, java.lang.Object, java.math.BigInteger) - as BigIntegers do not overflow.
      Type Parameters:
      K - Key
      Parameters:
      m - TreeMap
      k - key
      v - value
      Returns:
      The resulting value in m mapped by k.

      public static long[] getCounts​(java.util.HashSet s0, java.util.HashSet s1)

      Returns:
